Q4(8pts): Now generate box plots of the distributions of flight lengths for each carrier. Display both box plots in one plot (i.e. one call to boxplot). Use the formula FlightLength~Carrier and specify data=df.delays. Add the title:“Flight Lengths” and appropriate x and y axis labels.

boxplot(FlightLength~Carrier, data=df.delays, main="Flight Delays",ylab="Flight Length",xlab="Carriers")

Q5(5pts): Briefly explain what the boxplots show about the flight lengths of the carriers.

The boxplots shows that the carrier AA has a higher median and higher upper & lower quartiles, yet contains no outliers. On the other hand carrier UA has a smaller median and lower quartiles and has many outliers.

Q6(8pts): Compute the total delay time (y axis) for each destination (x axis) and plot these values in a barplot. Add the title: Total Delay per Destination, and label the x and y axes appropriately. You can use the tapply function to do the sum of the Delays for each destination. Lookup the tapply function with ?tapply if necessary. The second parameter you pass in to tapply is the “index” or “grouping” column, in this case Destination. The tapply function will apply the sum to Delay grouping on the levels of Destination- very nifty!

barplot(tapply(df.delays$Delay,df.delays$Destination,sum), main="Total Delays Per Destination", xlab="Destination",ylab="Total Delay Time")

Q7(2pts): Alter the plot so that the delays are shown in ascending order- i.e. the longest delay is at the right. Hint: use “sort”.

delaydestt <- tapply(df.delays$Delay,df.delays$Destination,sum)
barplot(sort(delaydestt,decreasing=FALSE), main="Total Delays Per Destination", xlab="Destination",ylab="Total Delay Time")

#### Part 2: Analyzing categorical data for independence: contingency tables.

You will perform a contingency table analysis on two data sets.

Process data sets.

Q8(2pts): You will work with the “TestProcessAB” data set. This data set contains the results, “good” or “bad” of making items from two processes A and B. Write the statement that reads in the file “TestProcessAB.csv” and assigns it to a variable df.process.

df.process<-read.table("TestProcessAB.csv", header = TRUE)

Q9(2pts): Create a table from the whole dataframe and assign it to a variable called cont.table and print the table to the console.

cont.table <- data.frame(df.process)

Q10(5pts): Inspect the table visually. Do you think there are any dependencies, or are the results independent of the process that generated them?

I think that all the results are fairly independent of the process that generated them seeing as some grade letters are not properly matched up with their results.

Q11(2pts): Write the statement that runs the chi-square test on the table.

cont.table <- table(df.process)

Q12(5pts): Interpret the results of the chi-square test above. Are the Good and Bad levels independent of the process A and B? Briefly explain why.

The results show that they are a bit dependent of the process as the p-value is less than 1.

Q13(6pts): Create a bar plot of the table, displaying the columns beside each other. Include a legend that identifies the Process. Use two different colors (or grey shades) for the bars and use the same colors for the legend. Dislay the legend at the top left.

reg.table <- table(df.process)
barplot(reg.table, main="Grades",xlab="Letter Grades",ylab="Results",legend = c("A's","B's"), args.legend = list(title="Grades", x="topleft", cex =.5))

Flight delay data.

Now analyze the FlightDelays data set. We want to know if destinations are realted to the number of delays of 30 minutes or more.

Q14(2pts):Read in the data file “FlightDelays.csv” if you haven’t already done so. Assign the data frame to the variable df.delays.

df.delays <- read.table("FlightDelays.csv", sep=",", header=TRUE)
flight.frame <- data.frame(df.delays)

Q15(5pts): Create a table from the columns Destination and Delayed30. You may use any way to access the columns- either by column name using the $ operator, or with bracket [] notation.

desdelay <- table(flight.frame$Delayed30,flight.frame$Destination)

Q16(2pts): Run the chi-square test on the table.

chisq.test(desdelay)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  desdelay
## X-squared = 36.246, df = 6, p-value = 2.469e-06

Q17(5pts): What are your conclusion(s)? Is there a dependency? Explain.

There is a high dependency as the P-Value is below 1%.

Q18(6pts): Create a barplot of the data with the columns beside. Include a legend. The legend will have two titles: “No delay” and “Delay”. Use two different colors for the columns and legend.

barplot(desdelay, xlab="Destinations", ylab="Time Delayed",legend = c("No delay", "Delay"), args.legend = list(title="Delayed 30?", x="topleft", cex =.5))
